# Scežka - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
- Next.js 15 with App Router
- TypeScript (strict mode)
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui
- Supabase (PostgreSQL + PostGIS)
- Yandex Maps API via @pbe/react-yandex-maps
- Zustand for client state
- TanStack Query for server state

## General Principles
- Prefer server components unless client interaction is needed (use 'use client' explicitly)
- Use TypeScript strict mode – no `any` type without a strong reason
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
- Use functional components with named exports
- Add JSDoc comments for complex logic, hooks, and utilities

## Code Style
- 2 spaces indentation
- Single quotes for strings
- Semicolons required
- Trailing commas in multi-line objects/arrays
- Max line length: 100 characters

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `PostModal.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with 'use' prefix (e.g., `usePosts.ts`)
- Utils/helpers: camelCase (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase, suffix 'Type' for types, no suffix for interfaces (e.g., `PostType` vs `Post`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

## Folder Structure (src/)
src/
├── app/ # App Router pages and layouts
├── components/ # Reusable UI components
│ ├── ui/ # shadcn/ui components (auto-generated)
│ ├── Auth/ # auth-related components
│ ├── Map/ # map components
│ └── Post/ # post/comment components
├── hooks/ # custom React hooks
├── lib/ # utilities, clients (supabase, etc.)
├── store/ # Zustand stores
└── types/ # shared TypeScript types (if not in database.types.ts)

## Supabase Best Practices
- Always use RLS policies – never disable them
- Use `@supabase/ssr` for server/client clients
- Prefer server-side data fetching where possible (server components)
- For real-time features, use `supabase.channel()` only in client components
- Use PostGIS functions (`ST_DWithin`, `ST_MakePoint`, etc.) for geo queries
- Never store plain text passwords; Supabase Auth handles it

## Yandex Maps Integration
- Use dynamic import with `{ ssr: false }` for any map component
- Load map only on client side
- Use `@pbe/react-yandex-maps` wrapper
- Coordinates: [latitude, longitude] order in JS, but `POINT(lng lat)` in PostGIS

## State Management
- Zustand: only for client-global UI state (theme, user session, filters)
- TanStack Query: for all server-state (posts, comments, routes)
- Local component state: useState/useReducer

## Error Handling
- Use try/catch with specific error messages
- Show user-friendly toasts for errors (using shadcn/ui toast)
- Log errors to console in development only
- Always handle loading and error states in components

## Git & Commits
- Use Conventional Commits: feat:, fix:, docs:, style:, refactor:, test:, chore:
- Keep commits atomic (one logical change per commit)
- Run `npm run lint` and `npm run format` before committing

## Security
- Never expose Supabase anon key or URL in client-side code (use env variables)
- Validate all user inputs on server side (even if validated on client)
- Use RLS policies as primary security layer

## Performance
- Use Next.js Image component for images
- Lazy load components with `next/dynamic` when not needed immediately
- Use React.memo for expensive components
- Implement pagination for lists (posts, comments)

## AI Assistant Instructions
When I ask you to generate code:
1. Follow the above conventions strictly.
2. Provide TypeScript types for all functions/components.
3. Include error handling and loading states where appropriate.
4. Add brief comments explaining non-obvious logic.
5. If you suggest a query to Supabase, ensure it's efficient (use select only needed columns).
6. For map-related code, always remember to use dynamic import and client component.
7. Prefer server components unless you need hooks or browser APIs.
